{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506792"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2572"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.54,0.03,0.33,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2572"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44782"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-day history of passing blood in his urine. He does not have dysuria, urinary frequency, or urgency. He also reports fatigue and weight loss over the past five months. He has a smoking history of 40 pack-years. On examination, his blood pressure is 132/80 mmHg, pulse 80/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The physical examination is unremarkable apart from a left-sided varicocele that fails to reduce when the patient lies down. His laboratory investigations are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin = 250 g/L (130-180 g/L) \u003Cbr /\u003EWBC = 8.4 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (3.5-11.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L) \u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets = 545 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows gross haematuria with 20-30 RBCs/hpf.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to be diagnostic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","CT scan abdomen","CT scan of the chest","Cystoscopy","Scrotal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s left-sided varicocele that fails to reduce when the patient lies down raises the suspicion for secondary varicocele caused by a mass in the retroperitoneal space. The most likely mass causing his varicocele is a renal cell carcinoma (RCC) evidenced by typical clinical findings (eg, gross haematuria, constitutional symptoms [eg, fatigue, weight loss], polycythaemia). Renal cell carcinoma is characterised by constitutional symptoms and a triad of symptoms (eg, haematuria, flank pain, palpable renal mass) caused by the primary tumour. However, not all patients present with the classical triad. A few patients may also have polycythaemia due to paraneoplastic production of erythropoietin. The diagnostic modality of investigation for patients suspected of RCC is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal CT scan with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E which may show renal enlargement with thickened irregular walls and calcifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriately sensitive for the diagnosis of benign renal cysts. CT scan with contrast is highly sensitive and specific for the diagnosis and staging of RCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E may be used for the staging of RCC to evaluate for metastasis since lungs are the most common locations for metastasis in RCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate if the patient is suspected of bladder cancer. Bladder cancer presents with gross haematuria with or without urinary frequency and urgency. Polycythaemia and secondary varicocele are unlikely to be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrotal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate for the diagnosis of testicular tumour. This patient\u2019s clinical findings and history are inconsistent with the diagnosis of a testicular tumour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most varicoceles are incidental findings, but in the presence of other symptoms, may have diagnostic significance.","A non-reducing left-sided varicocele in an older man can be a sign of renal cell carcinoma.","CT scan of the abdomen is the preferred diagnostic tool for suspected renal cell carcinoma."],"references":["Gray RE, Harris GT. Renal Cell Carcinoma: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Feb 1;99(3):179-184. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2019 Jun 15;99(12):732. PMID: 30702258. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30702258/","Bahadoram S, Davoodi M, Hassanzadeh S, Bahadoram M, Barahman M, Mafakher L. Renal cell carcinoma: an overview of the epidemiology, diagnosis, and treatment. G Ital Nefrol. 2022 Jun 20;39(3):2022-vol3. PMID: 35819037. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35819037/","Hsieh JJ, Purdue MP, Signoretti S, Swanton C, Albiges L, Schmidinger M, Heng DY, Larkin J, Ficarra V. Renal cell carcinoma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Mar 9;3:17009. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2017.9. PMID: 28276433; PMCID: PMC5936048. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28276433/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T21:21:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T21:23:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2572"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","syno